The article highlights the importance of addressing the health issues faced by veterans who were exposed to hazardous environments and substances during their military service. The bipartisan Sergeant First Class Heath Robinson Honoring our Promise to Address Comprehensive Toxics (PACT) Act, signed into law in August, is mentioned as the most significant expansion of benefits and services for toxic exposed veterans and survivors in over thirty years. The article also mentions that 500,000 PACT Act-related claims have been submitted to the Department of Veterans Affairs and three million veterans have received toxic exposure screenings since August. The Administration is processing claims at record rates to fulfill their obligation to care for veterans and their families. However, the article warns that Republican Members of Congress are proposing drastic cuts to VA programs, which could result in backlogs and reduced healthcare visits, thereby harming the veterans the PACT Act aims to help. The article concludes by stating that the Administration will continue to support veterans and oppose any efforts to cut critical services for them and their families.